library(nycflights13)
library(tidyverse)

Plots

  1. The count of flight hours of all the flights
hist(flights$hour)

  1. The scatter plot for departure delays and arrival delays.
ggplot(data = flights) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = dep_delay  , y = arr_delay, color = "blue")) +
  facet_wrap(~ carrier)

  1. The boxplot for departure delays and arrival delays.
ggplot(data = flights) + 
  geom_boxplot(mapping = aes(x = dep_delay  , y = arr_delay, color = "blue")) +
  facet_wrap(~ carrier)

  1. The relationship of the air time and the distance in bin2d
ggplot(flights) + 
  geom_bin2d(aes(air_time, distance)) +
  scale_fill_binned(low = "yellow", high = "blue")

5.The relationship of the air time and the distance in smooth

ggplot(flights) + 
geom_smooth(aes(air_time, distance))

Summary

What do you learn about the data from looking at the charts? The first chart illustrates the amount of the air time for all the flights. Most of the flights are in the air from 5- 20 hours while less than 5 hours or more than 20 hours are not very common. If we separate the carriers we can easily see which airline delays longer and often. The fourth chart and fifth chart tells us most of the flights fly longer if the distance is further.

Why did you choose to make those types f charts? I used the histogram because I want to see which hours are more common or less common for the all flights. The scatter plot helps me to see what are the hot spot for the total delay time from each carrier. The bin2d help me understand the relationship between the air time and the distance.
